<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900710-0054</DOCNO><DOCID>900710-0054.</DOCID><HL>   General Signal Agrees   To Sell Stepper Unit   To Employee Group</HL><DATE>07/10/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   GSX</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   STAMFORD, Conn. -- General Signal Corp. said it agreed tosell its Ultratech Stepper unit to an employee group in acash and paper transaction in which it will retain a minorityinterest. Precise terms weren't disclosed.   General Signal, a maker of process controls, electricalequipment and semiconductors, said Ultratech Stepperaccounted for about $40 million of its 1989 sales of $1.92billion. A stepper is a photolithography tool used to putcircuit designs on semiconductors.</LP><TEXT>   C. Woodrow Rea, a general partner in New EnterpriseAssociates, a San Francisco-based venture capital firm and aformer president of Ultratech, heads the employee group.Under the pact, General Signal will provide &quot;significantfinancing.&quot;   General Signal had planned to combine Ultratech, based inSan Francisco, with General Signal's GCA Stepper unit, whichhas about twice the sales of Ultratech. The agreement to sellUltratech, with about 300 employees, &quot;was a more attractivealternative to the risks associated&quot; with the merger plan, aGeneral Signal official said.   The transaction will allow General Signal &quot;to focus itsresearch and marketing efforts&quot; on the world-wide market forGCA Stepper's technology.</TEXT></DOC>